<div id="review_1963081" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1963081" />
    <a title="Jessica" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/129974-jessica"><img alt="Jessica" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1541091797p2/129974.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1963081?book_show_action=true">Jun 14, 2007</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jessica" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jessica" href="/user/show/129974-jessica">Jessica</a>
      </span>

          added it


          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780880015820" href="/book/show/1104411.The_Sheltering_Sky">review of another edition</a>

          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">Old Men</span></div>

        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1963081" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2279362715588605827">I rarely don&apos;t finish a book. This is a personal tendency (obsessiveness) which cemented itself during forays into such tomes as Les Miserables (5th grade) and Tess of the D&apos;Urbervilles (10th grade) in which the endeavor seemed like it would be fruitless, and then, ahoy! A beautiful gem on the sparkling sea surfaces, a hundred or so pages in, and I was rewarded for my patience...<br/>So it pains me to report that not even the chance of such a obscured jewel could keep me interested in A Sheltering Sk</span>
  <span id="freeText2279362715588605827" style="display:none">I rarely don't finish a book. This is a personal tendency (obsessiveness) which cemented itself during forays into such tomes as Les Miserables (5th grade) and Tess of the D'Urbervilles (10th grade) in which the endeavor seemed like it would be fruitless, and then, ahoy! A beautiful gem on the sparkling sea surfaces, a hundred or so pages in, and I was rewarded for my patience...<br />So it pains me to report that not even the chance of such a obscured jewel could keep me interested in A Sheltering Sky, which struck me as a poor man's Hemingway...make that a starving baby's Hemingway...in which the racism and misogyny are never once eclipsed by original prose. Nor did there seem to be much of a story...or if there was one, I couldn't give less of a shit about it. As Virginia Woolf once wrote, "All old men have their India." I'm going to leave this one to the old men.</span>
  <a data-text-id="2279362715588605827" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
