<div id="review_2208338853" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2208338853" />
    <a title="Alex" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3144945-alex"><img alt="Alex" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1594856152p2/3144945.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2208338853?book_show_action=true">Dec 08, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Alex" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Alex" href="/user/show/3144945-alex">Alex</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3144945-alex?shelf=2017">2017</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3144945-alex?shelf=dick-lit">dick-lit</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2208338853" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15974173641109199787">I&apos;m looking for a book about white people who drink too much, do you have anything like that? Oh right this way sir, right here in the front we have our White People Who Drink Too Much shelf. Wow there&apos;s a whole shelf, huh. Yes it turns out that nearly every single book ever written is about white people who drink too much. Gosh! Do they sometimes also have sex with each other in combinations that they later regret? Always, sir. Always. Oh good, I&apos;ve been wondering how white people who drink too</span>
  <span id="freeText15974173641109199787" style="display:none">I'm looking for a book about white people who drink too much, do you have anything like that? Oh right this way sir, right here in the front we have our White People Who Drink Too Much shelf. Wow there's a whole shelf, huh. Yes it turns out that nearly every single book ever written is about white people who drink too much. Gosh! Do they sometimes also have sex with each other in combinations that they later regret? Always, sir. Always. Oh good, I've been wondering how white people who drink too much might feel about having ill-advised sex with each other.<br /><br />Wait a minute though, because this one seems like it's taking rather a big swerve into existential horror here, isn't it? It's not that I didn't know people would die, I understand that they often do in these books, but I didn't quite expect it to be so...drawn out. It's all feeling a bit real here, which is, if we're being honest, unseemly. <br /><br />And then here at the end, well...well, I'm not sure what this is at all. It would seem to an untrained eye that <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[a man has written a semiautobiographical book in which he is betrayed by his own wife, whose weakness causes his death, and who is then gang raped more or less in penance for it, and likes it. <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span> Now, it can't possibly by this...baldly nasty, can it? Oh yes, sir, it can indeed, these men often are.<br /><br />Look: Book One is boring, Book Two is staggeringly brilliant, Book Three is extremely unpleasant business, so...what is that, three stars? Three stars and maybe I need another drink.<br /><br /><br /><b>Appendix: a story about Paul Bowles</b><br />Pointed out by <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/179714319" rel="nofollow noopener">my wonderful friend S.,</a> here's a story about going all the way to Morocco <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gBqpVsT-dGo&amp;feature=youtu.be&amp;t=1040" rel="nofollow noopener">to meet Paul Bowles.</a> I've linked you to the meeting part in case you don't have 20 minutes, but if you do have 20 minutes go ahead and listen to the whole thing, because it's not really about meeting Paul Bowles anyway, it's about being Edgar Oliver, who is one of those people who's decided to be exactly who he is all the time, which is something you can really only do if who you are is so weird that camouflage is difficult or impossible anyway. Like, I'm a little weird? But I can basically pass for normal, and so of course I do because it is <i>so much easier</i> to do literally everything when people aren't distracted by one's weirdness.<br /><br />When someone is weird you have to consider everything. What kind of weird is this person going to be, and how am I going to feel about it? When someone is weird all bets are off. Will he grope me in a stairwell. Will he offer me peyote and I'll suddenly have to try to remember whether I'm in favor of peyote or not. If it turns out they're just having a conversation about when Game of Thrones is coming back, you may find that it's hard to concentrate because you're so busy trying to decide whether they're wonderfully weird or creepily weird and why are they like whatever they're like. It is very difficult, and I've tried being weird a few times (or just been so high that it's the same thing) and you can tell people are doing all this. <br /><br />For the rest of us, those of us who can pass, we generally do, because it's much easier to get around when everyone has a basic expectation of how you might act in a given situation. You are likely to be sortof on time, and not start extremely intense conversations in coffee shops, and wear clothes, and not be high at surprising times, and be able to pay your share of the bill. These are comforting things to know. <br /><br />Anyway so the only people who really let their freak flags fly are the ones whose freak flags are too big to furl, and here we are with Edgar Oliver, somewhat of a NYC theater legend, who the minute he speaks and/or moves you're like oh, we have an original on our hands, so the 20 minutes of this story is really about just sort basking in Edgar Oliver being exactly who he is, which, for those of us who usually pass, is moving. What a difficult and special life he must lead.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15974173641109199787" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


